4.25.24  12:02 pm   how do you write chords you hear? i can hear chords in my mind but can't ever seem to figure out the name for what i'm hearing, despite understanding how chords work pretty good [competent jazz improviser, for example]

      i assume you have no trouble finding the notes, but it's just the naming that you're having trouble with. in that case, just get access to as many different song sheets as you can, and you'll eventually get the hang of how it's done. like english, not everything is written exactly the way it sounds, and not all of the sonic information is there. but it's just approximations that we have all grown accustomed to. through enough exposure, it will be impossible for you not to get it

4.23.24  6:42 pm   What do you think the function of a chord like D13sus4 (Cmaj7/D) is? You use that type of chord a lot and youve said that it can act as a suspended voicing of a 5, where in the example given, it would resolve to a G, but this never seems to happen in your songs, those chords tend to be an interjection of some sort like in  all of the times its used in "if the world doesnt end" for example on the lyric "been like that" its a F#maj7/Ab but there is no indication of a modulation to Db oh wait ive just realised as i wrote that that the song is in Db.  

      "been like that" is sort of 'key-of-the-moment'. no one really knows why this stuff works. when songwriting you have to just put on your magician cape, and just, make stuff happen

4.23.24  6:38 pm   got any advice for playing under pressue? when i play at home i can play flawlessly but when i play in front of a crowd my hands dont work and i hit wrong notes
